subsection.p:
The figure below shows the complex number z=3+3i, represented as a vector in the complex plane. The distance r from the origin to z is
r=\sqrt{3^2+3^2} = 3\sqrt{2}
and the angle from the real axis to the vector is \theta=\dfrac{\pi}{4}.

sidebyside.p:
Using right triangle trigonometry, we see that
\begin{align*}
  a \amp = 3\sqrt{2}\cos \dfrac{\pi}{4} = 3\sqrt{2} \cdot \dfrac{1}{\sqrt{2}} = 3\\
   b \amp = 3\sqrt{2} \sin \dfrac{\pi}{4} = 3\sqrt{2} \cdot \dfrac{1}{\sqrt{2}} = 3\\
    \end{align*}

solution.p:
 We compute
  r=\sqrt{a^2+b^2} = \sqrt{3+1} = 2~~~~\text{and}~~~~\tan \theta = \dfrac{1}{\sqrt{3}}
The angle \theta is in the first quadrant, so  
\theta = \tan^{-1} \dfrac{1}{\sqrt{3}} = \dfrac{\pi}{6}

subsection.p:
 Of course, we can always recover the Cartesian form of a complex number from its polar form by evaluating the trigonometric functions. We'll check the result of the previous example: 
\begin{align*}
  z \amp = 2(\cos \dfrac{\pi}{6} + i\sin \dfrac{\pi}{6})\\
    \amp = 2(\dfrac{\sqrt{3}}{2} + i \cdot \dfrac{1}{2} = \sqrt{3} + i\\
    \end{align*}

solution.p:
We use the polar form, z= 2(\cos \dfrac{\pi}{6} + i\sin \dfrac{\pi}{6}), and apply De Moivre's theorem. Then
 \begin{align*}
   z^4 \amp = 2^4(\cos 4 \cdot \dfrac{\pi}{6}+i\sin 4 \cdot \dfrac{\pi}{6})\\
   \amp=16(\cos \dfrac{2\pi}{3} + i\sin \dfrac{2\pi}{3})\\
   \end{align*}
   The Cartesian form of z^4 is thus 16(\dfrac{-1}{2} + i\dfrac{\sqrt{3}}{2}), or -8+8i\sqrt{3}.  You can check that you get this same result if you compute (\sqrt{3} + i)^4 by expanding the power.

subsection.p:
 As an example consider w=-8+8i\sqrt{3}, whose polar form is 16(\cos \dfrac{2\pi}{3} + i\sin \dfrac{2\pi}{3}), or by adding 2\pi to the argument, 16(\cos \dfrac{8\pi}{3} + i\sin \dfrac{8\pi}{3}). The two square roots of w are 
\begin{align*}
    z_1 \amp = 16^{1/2}(\cos \dfrac{\pi}{3} + i\sin \dfrac{\pi}{3})=4(\dfrac{1}{2} + i\dfrac{\sqrt{3}}{2}) = 2+2i\sqrt{3}\\
    z_2\amp=16^{1/2}(\cos \dfrac{4\pi}{3} + i\sin \dfrac{4\pi}{3})=4(\dfrac{-1}{2} + i\dfrac{-\sqrt{3}}{2}) = -2-2i\sqrt{3}\\
    \end{align*}

sidebyside.p:
You can verify that both of these numbers are square roots of w=-8+8i\sqrt{3}, for instance,
\begin{align*}
    (2+2i\sqrt{3})^2 \amp = 4+2(2)(2i\sqrt{3})+12i^2\\
    \amp=-8+8i\sqrt{3}\\
    \end{align*}
The graphs of w and its two square roots are shown at right.

solution.p:
Applying De Moivre's theorem to each of these expressions gives us two more cube roots
\begin{align*}
    z_2 \amp = 2(\cos \dfrac{2\pi}{3} + i\sin \dfrac{2\pi}{3}) = \dfrac{-1}{2}+i\sqrt{3}\\
    z_3 \amp= 2(\cos \dfrac{4\pi}{3} + i\sin \dfrac{4\pi}{3})= \dfrac{-1}{2}-i\sqrt{3}\\
    \end{align*}

assemblage.p:
A complex number z=r(\cos \alpha + i\sin \alpha) in polar form has n complex nth roots, given by
  z_k = r^{1/n}(\cos \dfrac{\alpha + 2\pi k}{n} + i\sin \dfrac{\alpha + 2\pi k}{n}
for k = 0,~1,~2, \cdots,~ n-1.

A complex number z=r(\cos \alpha + i\sin \alpha) in polar form has n complex nth roots, given by
  z_k = r^{1/n}(\cos \dfrac{\alpha + 2\pi k}{n} + i\sin \dfrac{\alpha + 2\pi k}{n}
for k = 0,~1,~2, \cdots,~ n-1.
